	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>New financial instrument to support the external dimension of the CFP </h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 January 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The EC has launched its proposal for a new financial instrument to support the EU's maritime and fisheries policies for the period 2014-2020: the European Maritime and Fisheries Fund (EMFF).</p><p>In a press release, the Commissioner stated that: ‘This new fund will increase economic growth and create jobs in the sector. No more money will be spent to build big vessels. Small-scale fisheries and aquaculture will benefit from this budgetary greening of the Common Fisheries Policy’. The press release also emphasises that there will be no more money for vessel scrapping: ‘Despite the €1.7 billion spent on scrapping since the 1990s, the EU fleet still suffers from overcapacity, as the decommissioning of vessels was offset by the technological upgrade of the remaining fleet’.</p><p>The EMFF proposal also covers technical assistance for fishing agreements and RFMOs, which, until 2013, are covered by another financial instrument. The EMFF proposal states (article 91): 'The EMFF may support, at the initiative of the Commission, subject to the ceiling of 1.1% of this fund: ... (b) the implementation of sustainable fisheries agreements and the Union participation in regional fisheries management organisations’.</p><p>The proposal also highlights that ‘In addition to the amount foreseen for the EMFF, an envelope is foreseen to cover sustainable fisheries agreements and EU membership in international organisations and regional fisheries management organisations, which have their own individual basic acts. The envelope for both actions amounts to €968 million’. The planned annual spending for SFAs and RFMOs varies between €146 million in 2014 and &nbsp;€136 million in 2020.</p><p>In an article in <i>Fish Update</i>, the European sector represented by Europêche and Copa-Cogeca recognised that ‘some of the sector's essential needs are relatively well covered by the Commission's proposal’, particularly provisions covering the promotion of human capital, social dialogue and on-board health and safety’. However, they regret that the Commission has proposed to end all financial support for scrapping vessels, despite the fact that many EU member states called for it to be maintained.</p><p>Environmental organisations generally recognise some positive steps, but claim that the proposal does not go far enough to support a transition towards sustainable fishing. In an article in <i>World Fishing </i><i>&amp; Aquaculture</i>, Greenpeace pointed out that ‘little funding has been set aside for enforcement of EU fishing rules and scientific assessments’, whilst the Ocean2012 coalition emphasised that many member states do not assess the capacity of their fishing fleets, which makes it difficult to assess whether this capacity is decreasing or not.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Proposal for a Regulation of the European Parliament and of the Council on the European Maritime and Fisheries Fund, 2 December 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/fisheries/reform/com_2011_804_en.pdf" target="_self">http://ec.europa.eu/fisheries/reform/com_2011_804_en.pdf</a></p><p><i>Europa Press Releases Rapid</i>, IP/11/1495, 2 December 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=IP%2F11%2F1495&amp;format=HTML&amp;aged=0&amp;language=EN&amp;guiLanguage=en " target="_self">http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=IP%2F11%2F1495&a...</a></p><p>Press article, <i>World Fishing &amp; Aquaculture</i>, ‘Enviro organisations respond to EU fund’, 6 December 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.worldfishing.net/news101/enviro-organisations-respond-to-eu-fund" target="_self">http://www.worldfishing.net/news101/enviro-organisations-respond-to-eu-fund</a></p><p>Press article, <i>FishUpdate.com</i>, ‘Europêche and Copa-Cogeca welcome proposal for new European Maritime and Fisheries Fund’, 6 December 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.fishupdate.com/news/fullstory.php/aid/16700" target="_self">http://www.fishupdate.com/news/fullstory.php/aid/16700</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Fishing agreements and RFMO participation are currently covered by separate financial instruments. Integrating the existing financial instruments into a single EMFF may simplify the system, and result in greater coherence between external and internal fisheries policies.</p><p>The fact that some extra funding for technical assistance is being set aside may give some flexibility to the EU in ensuring that monies spent through SFAs and RFMOs are tailored more to the needs of the third countries including ACP countries, rather than to the <i>pro rata</i> of the fishing possibilities negotiated. This may help to concretely ‘decouple’ the level of access from the level of funding, an important feature of the EC proposals on the external dimension of the CFP reform.</p><p>The fact that funds for scrapping will no longer be available is probably a positive step, as the relatively large funding allocated to scrapping in the past has not reduced EU fleet over-capacity. It is to be noticed that, after the non-renewal of the EU-Morocco agreement, and the foreseen reduction in fishing possibilities in some other current FPAs, certain member states have set aside monies for scrapping, to be used before 2014, in order to take advantage of the scrapping fund still in existence until then.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
